    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_58163509" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/58163509" />
    <a title="Karen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2050019-karen"><img alt="Karen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1244775600p2/2050019.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/58163509?book_show_action=true">Jun 02, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Karen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Karen" href="/user/show/2050019-karen">Karen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780671737641" href="/book/show/1404766.Whitney_My_Love">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2050019-karen?shelf=aar-top-100-2007">aar-top-100-2007</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer58163509" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14769191618271422594"><i>Whitney, My Love</i> should have been named <i>Whitney, I Love You/I Hate You/I Love You/I Hate You</i>. This had to be the single most frustrating book I have ever read. I loved the storyline and the characters for about the first 300 pages (my copy was 536 pages), but it went downhill for me after that. Someone asked why I didn&apos;t stop reading, but I was so invested after 300 pages that I had to see it through to the end. LOL <br/><br/>Just a brief summary...Clayton Westmoreland, the duke of Claymore met Whitney St</span>
  <span id="freeText14769191618271422594" style="display:none"><i>Whitney, My Love</i> should have been named <i>Whitney, I Love You/I Hate You/I Love You/I Hate You</i>. This had to be the single most frustrating book I have ever read. I loved the storyline and the characters for about the first 300 pages (my copy was 536 pages), but it went downhill for me after that. Someone asked why I didn't stop reading, but I was so invested after 300 pages that I had to see it through to the end. LOL <br /><br />Just a brief summary...Clayton Westmoreland, the duke of Claymore met Whitney Stone and decided that he wanted to marry her. Instead of getting to know her and asking <i>her</i>, he went to her father and paid off all his debt in exchange for his signature on a betrothal contract promising Whitney's hand in marriage. Once the contract was signed, Clayton set out to get to know Whitney and convince her that she wanted to marry him before they revealed his identity and the details of the contract. It was a really great premise for a regency romance.<br /><br />Here's what I didn't like...this couple had one earth shattering, I hate you, get out of my life and don't ever speak to me misunderstanding after another. At one point, I'm reading and I'm like "Oh no, Whitney. Destroy that letter. You know something's going to happen and Clayton will get the letter and then all hell will break loose." And that's exactly what happened.<br /><br />Even after they were married, Clayton drew his own conclusions about an event without speaking to Whitney and completely turned on her. How could she ever be secure in her marriage if he could cut her out of his life and deny his child because of something he <i>thought</i> had happened? I think this is the first time that I ever wanted the couple to break up because I wanted them to live the rest of their lives in misery with the knowledge of what they threw away. <br /><br />Ok...end rant. LOL I'm giving this book 3 stars based on the first 300 pages and because it was really well written even if annoyed me. </span>
  <a data-text-id="14769191618271422594" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

