    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_626860314" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/626860314" />
    <a title="[Aengell]" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7221205-aengell"><img alt="[Aengell]" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1431033477p2/7221205.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/626860314?book_show_action=true">May 28, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="[Aengell]" class="user" itemprop="url" name="[Aengell]" href="/user/show/7221205-aengell">[Aengell]</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7221205-aengell?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7221205-aengell?shelf=historical-romance">historical-romance</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer626860314" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10029152274859667370">--- Spoilers ahead!! ---<br/><br/>This book… Yeah. It brought me to my knees. I’m a wreck right now because of it, and I have to express this … turmoil inside of me <b>RIGHT</b> now, or else I wont be able to sleep tonight. <br/><br/>McNaught takes you to a roller coaster ride, with a promise that goes like this: You will cry. Then you will laugh. Then you will shake your head. You will repeat these motions again, again, and again. Yes, you will, reader mine, wether you want to or not. And you will love me because of this</span>
  <span id="freeText10029152274859667370" style="display:none">--- Spoilers ahead!! ---<br /><br />This book… Yeah. It brought me to my knees. I’m a wreck right now because of it, and I have to express this … turmoil inside of me <b>RIGHT</b> now, or else I wont be able to sleep tonight. <br /><br />McNaught takes you to a roller coaster ride, with a promise that goes like this: You will cry. Then you will laugh. Then you will shake your head. You will repeat these motions again, again, and again. Yes, you will, reader mine, wether you want to or not. And you will love me because of this roller coaster ride I’m taking you through. <br />This emotional disaster started after reading the first sentence in the novel, which actually brought me to tears. I’m too softhearted, I know, but I couldn’t hold it back. Judith McNaught’s husband is dead? I’m not used to these circumstances, romance writers often enough have a husband at home, which fits, because they write happy endings and… I don’t want to put my nose in things that don’t concern me, I know of your second husband, Mrs. McNaught, but I’m still sorry for the loss of Mister McNaught. Your dedication at the beginning melted my heart. <br /><br />So…<br /><br />The story starts with Whitney, the heroine, as a young girl, we get to know her as a impulsive, temperamental, crazy and funny child. She is in love with Paul, who is older than her and doesn’t care for her, just the opposite, he’s very annoyed with her childish adventures to „catch“ him. She becomes a belle in Paris, where she spends the next few years with her aunt and uncle, and where she has quite a string of admirers. <br />Clayton Westmoreland, the Duke of Claymore, sees her on some occasions in Paris and decides to marry her. Or rather to buy her from her indebted father. Whitney is sent back to England, and Clayton lives temporary in her village, as her neighbour, where he tries to win her heart with her not knowing his true identity. <br /><br />And there the <b>drama</b> begins. What the hell?! I had a real life, and then this novel came along and ruined everything. I feel so attached to the characters, it’s stupid. <br /><br />The secondary characters weren’t important at all, at least not in a good sense, they were just there to make Whitney or Clayton jealous, and me crazy with a NEED for violence. They were so annoying, just because I wanted the H/h to have their happy story. I know, I know, that would be boring, and you can say anything about this novel, but please don’t apply the word <i>boring</i>. <br /><br />Whitney: First I loved her. Because I read about the girl, the passionate, unusual girl with enough spunk and backbone to pine openly after her crush. Then I was proud of her because she grew up to be a beauty, to be sophisticated as well as original and bewitching. I was proud of her a long time, because she learned to play with the besotted fools at her feet (give it to them, girl!). I was annoyed, too, because although she had some experience , saw something of the world now, she was still thinking of Paul. I wanted to whisper: forget him, Whitney, play with these guys here, and there, about the corner, your one true love is lurking and watching. Which he did, actually. <br />When it comes to the part where she meets Clayton and interacts with him on several occasions, I had a bad feeling. Because I as the reader had a clear view. On the one hand was Paul, some nice looking fellow, not too intelligent, but not too stupid either. A darling with most women. And there was <i>HIM</i>. As in.. <i>
  <b>HIM</b>
</i>. Clayton, who is handsome, attractive, titled and all that stuff, yes, but who is also edgy, driven, headstrong. Who I grew to love.<br />And I can’t go into all those situations Whitney is put in, there are just to many, but I can say: she annoyed me because of her pining for Paul. She did it too long, she should have realised sooner that she isn’t really in love with him. And when various misunderstandings make their way between Clayton and her? She should have reacted better. She shouldn’t have been so weak. And so nice. That was really annoying. <br /><br />But you know what? Inspite of all these bad decisions and unfortunate behaviour of her’s, I love her. I truly do. Some may say that she is a weak heroine, that she is naive, but… She’s real! She’s an actual human being, living in the 19th century, with all her flaws and bad decisions. Yes she is. I don’t like 21st century women, feministic, anti-sexistic in a historical novel. Yeah, it just doesn’t do for me, because I think: well, yes, I want women to have been strong for the last 2000 years, too, but sorry. It didn’t work that way back then. And Mrs. McNaught did a great job here with the heroine, because although I got frustated at times, I FELT with Whitney, her pain, her happiness, her everything. Well done, dear author. <br /><br />Clayton. <br />Okay, I really don’t have a clue how to put this in the right way (so that everyone reading this understands my point of view), but I will try. <br />At the beginning I liked Clayton very much. He is not an unusual hero, but still. He is confident. He is cool. He is detached, and my little reader heart opened up for the romance between him and Whitney, because I knew that they would be good together. <br />Then comes the scene where he punishes Whitney for jeopardizing himself and the horse he is riding by throwing a stone at them. He beats her with the crop, on the bottom. In the reviews I read many many months ago, I think this scene was an issue with some readers? I hadn’t had a problem with it. One, because well, if this 19-year-old girl does something THAT childish? A child’s punishment is in order.Which leads me to two, which is the fact that at that time (shall I remind you again that we are talking about a good 150 years ago), punishing a child with a crop on the a** was regular. And also beating a women was okay, wether her father, her brother, or her husband did it. So no, I would never justify something like that, but yes, I think about the historical aspect of the novel and think: there’s nothing wrong. And it’s a very well-written scene, and if I read good literature, I don’t care what happens. Rather if it’s written so good that I can understand what happens, it is just that, good. <br /><br />Many readers hate Clayton for that, but also for the scene where he takes Whitney unwillingly. And I don’t live in a world which is black and white, so I don’t react the same way others may: Whitney really behaved stupid beforehand, and Clayton, fueled by his anger, does this thing to her. Which is, he forces her to have sex with him. But we get an insight into Whitney’s thoughts, while this is happening. So we know: she feels like she has deserved this punishment and wants to participate, or rather, to let him do it. He stops forcing her after he deflowers her, he doesn’t continue. And right after the moment he realises that she was a virgin until then, he regrets it and sees reality again. I absolutly <b>DO NOT</b> justify what he is doing, it is not correct to do something like that to a woman, no matter the circumstances. But McNaught makes me see his remorse, his guiltiness, his depression about what he has done, so that I forgive him, like Whithney does. For me it’s not about moral aspects or sexist aspects or whatever, for me it’s about an author who dares to write a very disturbing scene, happening between the main characters. And the reader doesn’t want this happening to the main characters, because of their sanctious status in the novel. But it <b>DOES</b> happen, and McNaught brought tears to my eyes in that scene. Simply because human do error, do make mistakes, do learn from them. And simply because noone can say: I would never do this and that when I love somebody sincerely. But <i>I</i> can’t vouche for my future behaviour, and I don’t think it unlikley that at some points I will make GREAT mistakes, but i'll regret them and I'll want to redo them and I'll still love the other person. <br />So again, just another proof of McNaughts great writing style. <br />From there on there are some misunderstandings and far too much time to wait until Clayton and Whitney come together again, but it’s a romance after all, so… <br /><br />With McNaught, when the characters love, they love as much as one can love, and when they hate, they hate as much as one can. But love and hate are so near, they are nearly indistinguishable, and Whitney and Clayton do both emotions very strongly. <br /><br />I have to say it again, in case I didn’t show my feelings enough: I absolutly loved this read, not because it was perfect in the sense of … perfect, but because it put me on the edge, it disturbed me, it frustated me, but I was 100% IN the story. I probably wont be able to reread it in the near future, it will definitly not be a reread for comfort, my heart couldn’t bear that. But I take a bow, Mrs. McNaught. I do. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10029152274859667370" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


